				 Bid to stem rupee rise
 OUR BUREAU																								Mumbai, Nov. 7: The government today raised the ceiling of market stabilisation bonds to enable the Reserve Bank to absorb excess liquidity to check the rise in the rupee, which is trading at its highest level in almost a decade.																								The Indian government, in consultation with the RBI, has further revised the ceiling for the outstandings under the market stabilisation scheme (MSS) for 2007-08 to Rs 2,50,000 crore. The threshold at which the ceiling will be reviewed in future will now be Rs 235,000 crore, the RBI said in a statement here.																								The earlier limit was Rs 200,000 crore. This is the fourth time the ceiling has been raised this fiscal  it was recently raised in October. The limit was raised as the government will borrow Rs 180,155 crore by tomorrow.																								MSS bonds is a mechanism to suck out excess liquidity arising out of the central banks intervention in the forex market to check the rising rupee. The rupee has strengthened more than 12 per cent against the dollar in 2007. It rose to 39.16 to a dollar in intra-day trade before settling at 39. 31.																								RBI panel																								The RBI today constituted an internal working group to examine the Radhakrishna expert committee report on agricultural indebtedness. The report has recommended bringing down rural indebtedness.																								Some UPA government leaders have demanded that debts of farmers with a land holding of less than two hectares should be waived and interest rates on farm loans reduced to 4 per cent. 																								They have also asked the government to declare debts taken from moneylenders as illegal and sought police protection for farmers. 
